The benefit of including the delimiters inside the body rather than in a header means that older client libraries can still operate correctly even if they do not explicitly support multi-part encoding. It's important

The convention for using a Content-Type and the `boundary` parameter is described below.
1) The client creates an array of the parts that will make up the request body. Each part has its own MIME headers, including at least one header specifying the Content-Disposition which tells the server what to do with the data when it arrives. For example: 
```swift
var parts:[MFPart]=[
    Part("part name", encodingName:NSUTF8StringEncoding),
    Part("filename","application/octet-stream")
        ]  
```
2) Then you can create an instance of NSMutableURLRequest and set the method, URL string, HTTP version and all other necessary parameters. Now you have two options to add the content type and the boundary: 
   * If your Swift framework depends on SystemConfiguration then use the following line to set both ContentType and Boundary
   ```arduino
   let postData = CFHTTPMessageCreate(kCFAllocatorDefault,HTTP_POST,request.HTTPVersion);
   [postData appendBytes:(void*)"\r\n"--myBoundary" length:17];
   // add your request body here in form of Data 
  [[request httpBody] writeToFileAtPath:url.absoluteString error:nil];
   free((__bridge void*)postData);
   ```
   * Otherwise if your dependency doesn't include SystemConfiguration, please use this code to set ContentType only, without any boundary separator
   ```csharp
   var postData : String { 
      return try! NSString(data: "<http://www.w3schools.com/>\r\nContent-Type:" + newValue!.contentType!, 
        encoding: NSUTF8StringEncoding)! 
    } 
  ```
  Note that in both cases, `newValue` variable refers to a valid value from a Content Disposition e.
